          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              At last we got back to the topic. About half way through the thread it looked like this was just created for a second place for people to complain about D3 being server side.<br /><br />I played D2 for only a short while, and the annoyances of the game made it nearly impossible for me to play. If I'm not playing hardcore, then I don't want gameplay that means I have to reroll if I make a mistake.<br /><br />I just started TL and after looking over the class skills, I went with what I thought would be fun. Later I found that I had chosen just about the most powerful build in the game. Since I'm a casual player and not likely to play TL again once D3 comes out, that is just peachy to me. I'm rolling with a freaking army, as in &quot;You mess wit' me, you mess wit' ma whole family!&quot; only in this case the family is already dead and reanimated as skeletons. OK, that got weird there at the end.<br /><br />Anyway, from what I played of D3 in the open beta, I think it will be better then TL1, and possibly better then TL2. It depends on how the balance is handled in both of them. I like that in D3 you don't have &quot;builds&quot; per se, just how you are currently configured with your abilities. <br /><br />Even in TL1 I've been bitten by some design choices I didn't agree with. In many games, if you sell something and change your mind you can buy it back. If you haven't left the store interface, you can often buy it back at cost, since it's like you just put your item down on the counter. In TL1, I accidentally sold a unique helmet I was wearing. I had swapped it out with one in my inventory to see the change, then, when I meant to right click it to reequip it, I shift clicked instead. The helmet sold for 200g. Well, I hadn't left the store interface, so I figured I would just buy it back, no harm/no foul. Except the buying price was over 14,000 gold. Bwhaaa? At that point, I cursed that I wasn't able to go all Skyrim on him and slaughter the merchant. A few other times, I've almost done this when the merchant, inventory, and pet inventory screens are all open. I'm used to shift clicking to quickly move things from the pet's inventory to my own, but that is a big no-no if the store is up as well.<br /><br />Also, small improvements from TL1 to TL2 that I've seen in the screen shots have given me hope. In TL1, the hotkeys were 1-0. Hitting 0 or 9 with your left hand during a fight isn't fun. In TL2, the screenshots show 1-5 and q-t, which is MUCH nicer. I would still prefer D3's solution as to just making everything rebindable in the GUI.<br /><br />Anyway, this kind of thread would be best once both games are released.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
