        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <span style="font-style: italic">Personal storytelling within. </span><br /><br />Spoilered to avoid wall-of-text &quot;me, me, me&quot; surprises.<br /><br /><div style="padding: 3px;">
  <div style="margin-bottom: 3px; font-weight: bold;" onclick="var q = $(this).parent().find('.quotecontent > div');q.toggle();$(this).find('span').html(q.is(':visible')?'hide':'show');return false;">
    <b>Spoiler: </b>
    <span style="color: #FF5B00; cursor: pointer;">show</span>
  </div>
  <div class="quotecontent">
    <div style="display: none;">
      Let&#39;s see ...<br /><br />2002ish, Dungeon Siege 1:  played it in a day and a bit, got to the end with all my purple gear, then tried to run it again, I couldn&#39;t face it. Instant ennui.<br /><br />Dungeon Siege 2:  Played it, &#39;oh dear, more of the same&#39;, and got a way through it before putting it aside and never looking at it again.<br /><br />Space Siege:  bought it in a fit of madness, and simply hated it.<br /><br />Diablo 1, it stayed full price for ages, I didn&#39;t get it until it was $3 from Good Old Games &#40;GoG&#41;, installed it, barfed at the graphics and left, in about 2009 I think.<br /><br />Torchlight -- $5, RAVE reviews, bought it, hated the &#39;isometric viewpoint&#39;, reminded me of Dungeon Siege, and then I went into a kind of coma where I couldn&#39;t possibly bear to even try with the damned game.  Put aside, never looked at it again.<br /><br />Diablo 3 : &quot;yawn&quot;, I said to myself, from its announcement through to the seemingly endless &quot;beta&quot;.  The day of release, I find the local shop-bought boxed version is -less- to buy than the online &#39;digital download&#39; version &#40;$AU59.99 is less than $US60, amirite?&#41;, so I bought it, knowing it was &#39;isometric loot hunting like dungeon siege&#39;.<br /><br />Except you&#39;re an overpowered monster killing machine!  It&#39;s just great fun mowing down the critters.  Then a special boss comes along, provides a few moments of &#39;oh oh, I might die&#39;, but hey, even if you do die, it doesn&#39;t matter, you just go back, re-arrange your powers to &#39;something appropriate&#39; and have at it.  I&#39;ve died about four times, once due to lag, twice due to not understanding the Skeleton King boss fight, and once due to multiplayer lunacy.  Each time it was painless, hopped straight back into the action.<br /><br />I didn&#39;t suffer any of the &#39;server unavailable&#39; crapola that upset 99.9% of their audience, and I&#39;ve never been disconnected from a session &#40;but I only play in 60-90minute chunks&#41;.<br /><br />With the town-portal, I don&#39;t have to worry about the tedious &#39;get all this junk back to the vendor&#39;, port, dump loot, port back, and I&#39;m back where I was, with the monsters patiently lurking in the dungeon, ready to HULK-SMASH when I get around to it.<br /><br />I&#39;ve easily put six or so hours into this game &#40;versus 15-20 minutes into Torchlight 1&#41;, and thought &quot;I wonder what powers I&#39;ll get next&quot; or &quot;lets roll &lt;x&gt; they look good&quot;, trying out various fighting and powers, pets and sidekicks.  It&#39;s got heaps of potential.  I see these pictures of people with &quot;700damage&quot; weapons and read of 21,000+DPS, and think &#39;wow, I&#39;m up to what, 70dps at L11, and having fun, how EPIC is this going to be when I get a LOT of gear!&quot;<br /><br />Played multiplayer with some friends from WoW who just got the game on the weekend, and it was great, truly rocking fun!  We got loot, smashed through quests, killed stuff that would have wiped the floor with any of us solo.  It was all too short by the time we finished.  40 minutes of multiplay at L9, got more more gold than I&#39;d earned in five or so hours of solo.<br /><br />D3&#39;s internet requirement is no more &#39;damaging&#39; than MMORPG &#39;always on&#39; requirements, it just makes things simpler for all.  ESPECIALLY the reduction in cheaters, and the AH, whilst a bit of a pain, is almost usable &#40;why can&#39;t I search for specific names of gear, dammit!&#41;, enabling even relatively poor people to equip characters with level-appropriate gear for a song.<br /><br />Saying &quot;I love it&quot; would be hyperbole.  I&#39;m imagining that I&#39;ll be playing this game for a long long time, as I investigate the various playstyles and weapon choices.  One really rare drop should enable me to block-buy all the Stash unlocks; I don&#39;t HAVE to engage in the tedious Crafting charade.  The shared-between-all-characters stash means that my high level guys can equip my low level guys with their rubbish drops, and make the low level guys -rock-.  Win-win!<br /><br />D3 really is polished and smooth, and an amazing game experience.  I loved Dungeon Siege -- once.  I think D3 will have much more repeatability.
    </div>
  </div>
</div><br /><br />Back to the 'either/or' debate.<br /><br />(I am definitely in the &quot;why not have both&quot; camp. Sheesh, poor people are so dull  <img src="//cdn.arstechnica.net/civis/images/smilies/razz.gif" alt=":P" title="Razz Animated" /> ).

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
     
